============================================================
        ADVANTAGES OF WORKING WITH FRAMEWORKS
============================================================

=> Frameworks provide abstraction on one or more technologies
   and simplify the application development process

=> In framework-based application development:
   - There is NO boilerplate code problem

=> APIs/Libraries of frameworks are designed by keeping
   real-time use cases/scenarios in mind

=> Developing projects using frameworks is:
   - Faster
   - Easier
   - More maintainable

=> Frameworks have become the industry de-facto standard
   to develop applications


============================================================
   TYPES OF JAVA FRAMEWORKS (BASED ON APPLICATION TYPE)
============================================================

a) ORM Frameworks
b) Web MVC Frameworks
c) Web Service Frameworks
d) JEE / Application Frameworks


============================================================
                 ORM FRAMEWORKS
============================================================

ORM = Object Relational Mapping


------------------------------------------------------------
1. PERSISTENCE
------------------------------------------------------------

=> The process of storing and managing data for a long time
   is called PERSISTENCE

=> The place where data is stored for a long time
   is called PERSISTENCE STORE

Examples of Persistence Stores:
- Files
- Databases (DB)


------------------------------------------------------------
2. PERSISTENT DATA
------------------------------------------------------------

=> Data that is stored in persistence stores is called
   PERSISTENT DATA

Examples:
- Files  -> File data
- DB     -> Table records


------------------------------------------------------------
3. PERSISTENCE OPERATIONS (CRUD)
------------------------------------------------------------

Operations performed on persistent data are called
PERSISTENCE OPERATIONS

CRUD Operations:
C -> Create (Insert)
R -> Read   (Select)
U -> Update (Modify)
D -> Delete (Remove)


------------------------------------------------------------
4. PERSISTENCE LOGIC
------------------------------------------------------------

=> Logic written to perform persistence operations
   is called PERSISTENCE LOGIC

Examples:
- IO Streams code
- JDBC code
- Hibernate code


------------------------------------------------------------
5. JAVA APP + PERSISTENCE STORES
------------------------------------------------------------

Java App
  |
  |-- IO Streams logic  --> Files
  |
  |-- JDBC logic        --> DB (Oracle, MySQL, PostgreSQL)


=> Since files have many limitations, databases are preferred
   as persistence stores


============================================================
LIMITATIONS OF JDBC-BASED PERSISTENCE DEVELOPMENT
============================================================

a) JDBC persistence logic is DB-dependent
   - Uses DB-specific SQL queries

b) JDBC code is NOT portable across multiple databases
   - Changing DB increases complexity

c) ResultSet object is NOT serializable
   - Cannot be sent over network easily

d) JDBC programming uses checked exceptions
   - Programmer must handle exceptions explicitly

e) JDBC code has boilerplate code problem
   - Same logic repeated in multiple projects
   - Minor changes affect many files


============================================================
       SOLUTION â€“ ORM FRAMEWORKS
============================================================

=> To overcome JDBC problems, ORM frameworks are used

=> ORM frameworks provide:
   - DB-independent persistence logic
   - Abstraction over JDBC
   - Automatic SQL generation


Examples of ORM Frameworks:
- Hibernate
- iBatis
- TopLink
- EclipseLink


============================================================
            WHAT IS ORM (O/R MAPPING)?
============================================================

=> Mapping Java classes with DB tables is called ORM

=> Mapping Java object properties with DB table columns
   is called O/R Mapping

=> Synchronization between:
   - Java objects
   - DB table records
   is called ORM


------------------------------------------------------------
SYNCHRONIZATION
------------------------------------------------------------

=> Synchronization means:
   - Changes in object reflect in DB
   - Changes in DB reflect in object


============================================================
           ENTITY CLASS (PERSISTENCE CLASS)
============================================================

=> A Java class that represents a DB table
   is called ENTITY CLASS or PERSISTENCE CLASS

Example:
- Student class  -> student_table

Fields Mapping:
- Java variables -> DB columns


============================================================
      ORM FRAMEWORK WORKING (HIGH LEVEL)
============================================================

Java App
  |
  |-- Create Java objects
  |
ORM Framework (Hibernate)
  |
  |-- Converts objects to SQL queries
  |
JDBC
  |
  |-- Executes SQL queries
  |
Database


=> ORM framework internally uses JDBC
=> Programmer does NOT write JDBC code directly


============================================================
   ORM FRAMEWORKS IN JAVA (SOURCE)
============================================================

Hibernate     -> From JBoss
iBatis        -> From Apache
TopLink       -> From Oracle
EclipseLink   -> From Eclipse


============================================================
 ORM IN SPRING / SPRING BOOT
============================================================

=> Spring does NOT have its own ORM framework

=> Spring provides ORM / Data JPA modules that provide
   abstraction over existing ORM frameworks

Examples:
- Spring ORM (Hibernate / iBatis)
- Spring Data JPA


------------------------------------------------------------
SPRING DATA JPA FLOW
------------------------------------------------------------

Developer
  |
Spring / Spring Boot ORM or Data JPA
  |
Hibernate / iBatis
  |
JDBC
  |
Database


=> DB understands only SQL queries
=> JDBC is required internally
=> Developer never writes JDBC code directly
=> Indirect usage of JDBC happens via ORM frameworks


============================================================
               KEY ADVANTAGES OF ORM
============================================================

- No DB-dependent SQL
- No boilerplate code
- DB portability
- Faster development
- Cleaner persistence logic
- Better maintainability

